Automate all the above steps¶

In [27]:
#Creating a function to remove samples with missing values and one hot encode categorical data
def clean_and_encode(df_name):
    # Replacing blank values and invalid data if any with null values which can be treated
    df_name = df_name.replace(r'^\s*$', np.nan, regex=True)
    print(df_name.info())
    df_name.isnull().sum()
    series1 = df_name.isnull().sum()
    for i in series1:
        if(i!=0):
            df_name.dropna(inplace=True)
            print('data has missing values and the corresponding samples have been removed')
            break
    else:
        print('data has no missing values')
    
    print(df_name.info())
    
    #One Hot Encoding:
    for columns in df_name:
        if (df_name[columns].dtype != ('float64'or'int64'or'unit8')):
            df_name[columns] = pd.get_dummies(df_name, columns=df_name.columns)
    
    df_name.info()

#Trying the function on a copy of our dataframe    
clean_and_encode(df_copy)

Check for target balancing and fix it if found imbalanced.¶

In [60]:

Out[60]:
0    5163
1    1869

In [61]:
# The target classes are imbalanced. The number of churned customers is lower than the ones who have not churned.
# Among the various target balancing techniques available, we will use SMOTE which is an upscaling technique for this case considering the size of the dataset. 
# Downsampling on the other hand would lead to information loss which we cannot afford except for in huge datasets.
# It is better to do target balancing only on train data and not test data. Hence we have performed train-test split before target balancing.
# This is to keep test data as close to real life data as possible and to avoid data leakage from training data to test data as in SMOTE, synthetic data created from training instances could get into the test set if we did SMOTE before split on whole data.
In [62]:
# It is better to scale the data before we use SMOTE as it is based on KNN
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler 
sc = StandardScaler() 
X_train = sc.fit_transform(X_train) 
X_test = sc.transform(X_test)  
#Here we do not fit X_test separately, since we want to use the same scaling as X_train. Since all must be on same scale

Check if the train and test data have similar statistical characteristics when compared with original data.¶

In [66]:
# Using 2 tailed t test between test data and original data:

from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
t_statistic, p_value = ttest_ind(y, y_test)
print(t_statistic, p_value)
if p_value < 0.05:    # alpha value is 0.05 or 5%
   print(" we are rejecting null hypothesis. That is test data target attribute statistical charecterestics differ significantly from that of the original data")
else:
  print("we are accepting null hypothesis. That is there is no significant difference in the target attribute statistical charecterestics between test data and original data")

if p_value < 0.05:    # alpha value is 0.05 or 5%
   print(" we are rejecting null hypothesis. That is train data target attribute statistical charecterestics differ significantly from that of the original data")

Model training, testing and tuning¶

Train and test all ensemble models taught in the learning module.¶

Display the classification accuracies for train and test data.¶

In [69]:
# Function to train and test models

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

def fit_and_print(model,X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test):

  model.fit(X_train,y_train)

  pred = model.predict(X_test)

  train_score = model.score(X_train,y_train)
  test_score = model.score(X_test, y_test)

  print("Train Score:", train_score)
  print("Test Score:", test_score)
  print(confusion_matrix(y_test,pred))
  print(classification_report(y_test,pred))
In [83]:
# Bagging Classifier Model:

from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

bc = BaggingClassifier(
    DecisionTreeClassifier(), n_estimators=200,
    max_samples=100, bootstrap=True, n_jobs=-1)

fit_and_print(bc,X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test)

Display and compare all the models designed with their train and test accuracies.¶

classifiers = [bc, rf, gb, ab, xb, lb, cb, stc]
Trn_Scr = []
for i in classifiers:
    Trn_Scr.append(i.score(X_train, y_train))

Tst_Scr = []
for i in classifiers:
    Tst_Scr.append(i.score(X_test, y_test))
    
Ensemble = ['Bagging', 'Random_Forest', 'Grad_Boost', 'Ada_Boost', 'XG_Boost', 'LightGBM', 'Cat_Boost', 'Stacking']

arr1 = np.column_stack([Ensemble, Trn_Scr, Tst_Scr])
arr1
column_values = ['Ensemble_Model', 'Training_Score', 'Test_Score']
df_score = pd.DataFrame(data = arr1, columns = column_values)
print(df_score)
df_score['Training_Score'] = df_score['Training_Score'].astype('float')
df_score['Test_Score'] = df_score['Test_Score'].astype('float')
from pylab import rcParams
rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 15, 7
df_score.plot(x='Ensemble_Model', y = ['Training_Score', 'Test_Score'], kind='bar')

# For this use case of predicting customers most likely to churn, both precision and recall are important metrics.
# Test Accuracy score could be misleading due to the class imbalance in test set.
# Neither False Positives not False Negatives are desirable for our case and must be minimized.
# High False positives (low precision) would make the company focus its retention efforts on incorrectly predicted customers who are actually not going to churn
# High False negatives (low recall) would cause the company to miss to identify the actual customers who will churn
# Hence in my opinion, the macro average (which takes into account the class imbalance) of F1 score (which is derived from both precision and recall) is the most important metric for this scenario.
# Both Random Forest and Bagging classifiers have the highest F1 score (macro average) of 0.74.
# Since Random Forest has a lot more hyperparameters for optimizing compared to Bagging model, I choose Random forest as the best trained model for this dataset.

import pickle

Pkl_Filename = "Pickled_RF_Model.pkl"  
with open(Pkl_Filename, 'wb') as file:  
    pickle.dump(rf, file)

# Loading the pickled model back from file and using it.
with open(Pkl_Filename, 'rb') as file:  
    Pickled_RF_Model = pickle.load(file)
Pickled_RF_Model.predict(X_test)

Conclusion and improvisation¶

Write your conclusion on the results.¶

Final Model's Performance:¶

  • The final best trained model classifies customers as either likely to churn or unlikely to churn with an accuracy of around 78% on test data
  • Out of the 1407 customers in test data, the model has correctly predicted 832 customers as not likely churn.
  • And 264 customers have been correctly pedicted as likely to churn.
  • 208 customers who actually did not churn were incorrectly predicted as likely to churn
  • 102 customers who actually churned were incorrectly predicted as not likely to churn
  • The model has a macro average F1 score of 0.74. Macro Average F1 Score was determined to be the most important metric for this dataset.

Further steps to improve model:¶

  • It should be possible to perform hyperparameter tuning to improve the classification.
  • During the visualization stage, it was observed that the target variable did not have strong correlation with any of the input variables, which could be a cause for poor classification metrics.
  • It might be possible to improve the classification through feature engineering by eliminating or combining features with low correlation into ones that have higher correlation and hence more predicting power.

Suggestions for the telecom company to reduce churn rate:¶

  • It was identified that customers who were senior citizens/ new customers with low tenure/ customers with high monthly charges/ customers using Fiber Optic Internet Service, Paperless Billing & Electronic Cheque as payment method were most likely to churn.
  • Hence the company could focus their efforts on these categories of customers to improve their experience so that chrun rate could get reduced.

Detailed suggestions or improvements or on quality, quantity, variety, velocity, veracity etc. on the data points collected by the telecom operator to perform a better data analysis in future.¶

  • It was observed from the correlaton analysis that none of the input features seem to influence the likelyhood of customer churn much (no strong correlation).
  • Hence further research could be done to identify and include additional customer attributes if any which have more impact on customer churn.
  • Since the dataset is not balanced considering target classes, if the number of samples collected is very high, we could afford to downsample the majority class to match the minority class. This will avoid the need for synthetic data creation (upsampling) which changes the statistical charecterestics of the dataset.
  • Few samples had missing values in Total Charges feature, which could have been avoided.
